metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: Out of window #123
metadata.description:
The work is part of a digital art movement that integrates art, mathematics, and physics in the creation of new works of art.
In my work, I deconstruct materials and investigate the nature of bodies and their components, which has some overlap with experimental particle physics. Particle accelerator experimental devices produce a set of geometric shapes and lines, which I have used in this work. Various exotic particles are created through acceleration, filtering, and collisions. It is often my intention to question relationships between objects and contexts, reality and imagination, and realism and abstraction using imaging and machine learning methods. This project is very close to what I think of as the machine mentality that by imagination is activated as demarcation and categorization critique, it conforms.

Made by, p5.js - CSG.js

metadata.name: Automata cotton fabrics #8
metadata.description: Ever since I was a kid, I used to love the feel of woven cotton fabrics with their colourful and funky patterns, especially the ones with irregular designs or erroneous aberrations. Later when I first came across the cellular automata algorithm, I was impressed by the ingenuity of the code and imagined it as a base for generating abstract designs, resulting in some fabrics of my imagination.

metadata.name: Wonderscapes #117
metadata.description:
In the infinite abyss of wondering there are some random moments of beauty which will stay in memory and at the end they will remind us that exploration and efforts were not in vain.

This artwork is rendered in real-time using custom webStyleGAN model (~25mb) which was trained on a dataset of about 5000 wonderscapes generated by DALL-E from OpenAI.

In addition to the main generative model, there is a CNN classifier model that filters the rendered images by predicting similarity to landscapes (this may take some time with each generation).

On top of the image generated by the neural network, there is a processing script that converts the value of each pixel into a colored ASCII character, the final result is a 64x64 vector grid with 4096 text symbols.

Controls:
- Press [s] to save the high resolution image

metadata.name: Reaction Diffusion Cellular Automata #49
metadata.description:
Cellular Automata (CA) model for Belousov‚ÄìZhabotinsky (BZ) Reaction Diffusion system.

In BZ system non linear chemical oscillators give rise to pattern formation, large scale ordered patterns emerge from chaotic initial conditions.

The CA model gives rise to spiral waves patterns using only local interactions.

Each unique minted token has a randomly chosen starting condition and color palette.
